      "Florence, meanwhile, had a problem that had embarrassed the city for decades. Its magnificent cathedral, Santa Maria del Fiore, stood with a gaping hole at its crossing where an enormous dome was supposed to be. The opening was so wide that no one knew how to vault it. The conventional method required a vast wooden framework to support the masonry while it set, but a frame strong and large enough simply could not be built.",
      "In 1418 a competition was held, and Brunelleschi won it with a plan so daring that the overseers at first doubted his sanity. He proposed to raise the dome with no centring frame at all. He designed two shells, an inner structural dome and an outer protective one, and used a self supporting herringbone pattern of bricks that locked into place as they were laid, allowing the dome to rise course by course under its own logic.",
      "To make it possible he invented the machinery itself: ingenious ox driven hoists with reversible gears that could raise and lower hundreds of tons of stone, brick and marble high into the air, and even a system to bring food up to the workers so they need not climb down for lunch. Begun in 1420 and largely completed by 1436, the dome remains the largest masonry dome ever built.",
      "Brunelleschi did more than crown a cathedral. He is also credited with rediscovering the mathematical rules of linear perspective, giving painters the tools to depict convincing three dimensional space on a flat surface. In both feats he embodied a new kind of figure, the architect engineer who reasons from first principles, and in doing so he helped to launch the Renaissance itself.",
      "The dome spans roughly forty five meters and consumed more than four million bricks, and Brunelleschi's design for the marble lantern that crowns it was carried out only after his death. In 1421 he received what is often called one of the first modern patents, a three year monopoly on a river boat he devised to haul marble. Beyond the dome he gave Florence the serene Ospedale degli Innocenti, the Basilica di San Lorenzo and the Pazzi Chapel, foundational buildings of Renaissance architecture, and he was buried with honour inside the cathedral he had completed.",
