      "He lived at the crossroads of two worlds that the Renaissance was busy uniting: the abstract mathematics of the scholars and the practical arithmetic of the merchants who were building Italy's commercial wealth. Pacioli understood both, and he had a gift for explaining them clearly.",
      "In 1494 he published his great work, the Summa de arithmetica, geometria, proportioni et proportionalita, a vast survey of everything known about mathematics in his day, written not in Latin but in Italian so that ordinary merchants could read it. It was one of the first mathematical books to be printed, and it circulated widely thanks to the new technology of the printing press.",
      "Tucked inside this encyclopedia was a section that would make Pacioli famous for centuries. He described, clearly and in print for the first time, the system of double entry bookkeeping that Venetian merchants had been developing in practice. In this method every transaction is recorded twice, once as a debit and once as a credit, so that the accounts must always balance, instantly revealing errors and giving a true picture of a business.",
