      "As a teenager he was apprenticed in Florence to the artist Andrea del Verrocchio, where he learned painting, sculpture and the mechanics of the workshop. He quickly surpassed his master, but his curiosity refused to stay within the bounds of any single craft. To Leonardo, art and science were not separate pursuits but two ways of seeing the same reality, and he gave himself permission to investigate absolutely everything.",
      "As a painter he produced some of the most revered images in history. The Mona Lisa, with its elusive smile and atmospheric depth, and The Last Supper, with its psychological drama, changed the course of Western art. Yet he completed surprisingly few paintings, forever pulled away by other questions, and some major commissions he left unfinished as his attention wandered to a new problem.",
      "His private notebooks, thousands of pages written in mirror image script, reveal the true scope of his mind. They overflow with designs for flying machines, a helicopter like aerial screw, parachutes, armoured fighting vehicles, multi barrelled guns, diving apparatus, automated looms and grand schemes to divert rivers, alongside meticulous studies of water in motion, the growth of plants, the formation of rocks and the play of light and shadow.",
