      "Drawn from commerce into exploration, Vespucci took part in several voyages to the New World in the years around 1500, sailing along great stretches of the eastern coast of South America. A skilled navigator with a sharp eye for the natural world, he observed the coastlines, the stars of the southern sky, the peoples, plants and animals with the curiosity of a true investigator.",
      "His crucial insight grew out of that careful observation. Christopher Columbus had gone to his grave insisting that he had reached the outskirts of Asia. But Vespucci, studying the immense, continuous coastline stretching endlessly southward and the unfamiliar constellations overhead, drew a different and revolutionary conclusion. This was not Asia at all. It was a vast landmass entirely unknown to the geographers of the ancient world, a genuinely New World.",
      "He described his findings in letters that were printed and circulated widely across Europe, written in a vivid, accessible style that captured the public imagination far more than dry official reports. For the first time, educated Europeans began to grasp that their map of the globe was fundamentally incomplete.",
      "In 1507 a German cartographer named Martin Waldseemüller, drawing an ambitious new map of the world that incorporated these discoveries, decided to honour the man whose letters had explained the new continent. He labelled the southern landmass America, a Latinised, feminine form of Amerigo's first name.",
      "The name caught on, spread to the northern continent as well, and eventually to the entire hemisphere. The result is one of history's great quirks: the explorer who first understood that a new continent existed never set out to have it named for him, yet Amerigo Vespucci became the only person in history to have two continents, North and South America, bear his name.",
