      "From the start he insisted on a radically different way of doing science. Where scholars of his day settled questions by quoting Aristotle and the ancients, Galileo demanded that nature be interrogated directly, through careful observation, measurement and experiment, and described in the precise language of mathematics. He once wrote that the book of the universe is written in the language of mathematics.",
      "His studies of motion overturned two thousand years of belief. He argued, and demonstrated, that objects of different weights fall at the same rate when air resistance is removed, contradicting Aristotle. By rolling balls down inclined planes he showed that falling bodies accelerate according to a simple mathematical rule, work that pointed directly toward the laws of motion later completed by Isaac Newton.",
      "In 1609, hearing of a Dutch device that made distant things appear near, Galileo built his own greatly improved telescope and did something no one had truly done before: he turned it systematically on the night sky. What he saw shattered the ancient picture of a perfect, unchanging heavens. He found mountains and craters on the Moon, spots on the Sun, countless unseen stars, the phases of Venus, and four moons circling Jupiter, proof that not everything in the cosmos revolves around the Earth.",
      "These discoveries convinced him that the Earth orbits the Sun, as Copernicus had proposed. Galileo championed this view publicly and brilliantly, but in doing so he collided head on with the authority of the Catholic Church, which held that the Earth stood fixed at the center of creation. In 1633 he was summoned before the Inquisition, tried, forced to publicly recant, and condemned to spend the rest of his life under house arrest.",
