      "His saints and apostles had dirty feet and weathered faces. He used beggars, laborers and women from the street to portray the holiest figures of Christianity, lending his religious scenes a shocking, almost confrontational reality. To some patrons this was sacrilege; to others it was a thrilling new intensity that made the sacred feel immediate and human.",
      "His signature was his command of light. Caravaggio plunged his backgrounds into deep darkness and let a single shaft of light fall across his figures, modeling them with stark contrasts of brightness and shadow. This technique, called chiaroscuro and, at its most extreme, tenebrism, gave his paintings a charged, theatrical drama. In works like The Calling of Saint Matthew, light itself becomes the divine actor, picking a man out of the gloom.",
      "His life was as dramatic as his canvases. Quick tempered and often armed, he was repeatedly in trouble with the law, and in 1606 he killed a man in a brawl and had to flee Rome with a price on his head. He spent his last years a fugitive, painting masterpieces in Naples, Malta and Sicily while running from his past.",
      "He died in obscurity in 1610, only thirty eight years old, possibly of fever on a beach while trying to return to Rome for a pardon. Yet his revolution could not be contained. His dramatic realism and his theatrical use of light swept across Europe, shaping Rubens, Rembrandt, Velázquez and the entire Baroque era. Centuries later, his cinematic instinct for light and shadow would feel uncannily modern, echoing in the language of film itself.",
