      "Torricelli devised an elegant experiment to investigate. Reasoning that mercury, being far denser than water, would behave the same way at a much smaller scale, he filled a glass tube about a meter long with mercury, sealed one end, and upended it into a dish of mercury. The mercury fell, but only partway, settling at a height of around seventy six centimeters and leaving an empty space at the top of the tube.",
      "From this simple result Torricelli drew two revolutionary conclusions at once. The mercury was being held up not by any abhorrence of emptiness but by the weight of the atmosphere pressing down on the dish, the air itself had weight and exerted pressure. And the space at the top of the tube was a true vacuum, something philosophers since antiquity had declared impossible.",
      "Without quite intending to, he had invented the barometer, the first instrument to measure atmospheric pressure, and laid the foundations of meteorology. More profoundly, he had proven that air has weight and that vacuums can exist, insights that opened the way to the study of gases and pressure and, ultimately, to the steam engines that would power the industrial age. He died of fever at just thirty nine, but the unit of pressure, the torr, keeps his name alive.",
