      "Marcello Malpighi was an Italian physician, biologist and professor at the University of Bologna who became one of the founding figures of modern biology. He worked at the dawn of a new age of discovery, when the recently invented microscope was opening up a realm of life far too small for the naked eye to see.",
      "Where others used the instrument only for casual curiosity, Malpighi turned it into a serious tool of research, systematically examining the fine structure of living tissues. In doing so he effectively founded the science of microscopic anatomy, known today as histology, the study of the body at the level of its tissues.",
      "His most celebrated discovery resolved one of the great unanswered questions of medicine. The English physician William Harvey had argued that blood circulates continuously around the body, pumped out through the arteries and returning through the veins, but he could not explain how the blood passed from one to the other, since no connecting vessels could be seen.",
      "Examining the lung of a frog under his microscope in 1661, Malpighi saw the answer. He observed a fine, dense network of tiny vessels, the capillaries, linking the smallest arteries to the smallest veins and completing the circuit of circulation. It was the missing piece of Harvey's theory, found at a scale no one had been able to reach before.",
      "He went on to describe the microscopic structure of many organs, the kidneys, the spleen, the skin, the liver and the lungs, as well as the development of the chick embryo and the anatomy of insects and plants. So many features still carry his name, from layers of the skin to structures in the kidney and spleen, that his influence is written into the vocabulary of medicine itself.",
      "Malpighi's patient, meticulous observation carried a profound message: the secrets of life lay hidden at scales the unaided eye could never perceive, and understanding the body meant looking ever closer. He set biology firmly on the path that would lead, in the centuries after him, to the discovery of cells and the foundations of all modern medicine.",
      "In 1669 he became the first Italian elected a fellow of the Royal Society of London, which published much of his later work, and he is counted among the founders of plant anatomy and embryology as well as microscopic anatomy. His name is scattered throughout the body, in the Malpighian layer of the skin, the Malpighian corpuscles of the kidney and spleen, and the Malpighian tubules of insects. In his final years he served as personal physician to Pope Innocent XII in Rome, where he died in 1694.",
