      "Antonio Meucci was born in Florence and trained at the Academy of Fine Arts, where he studied design and mechanical engineering. He began his career as a stage technician in the theaters of Florence, work that gave him a practical, hands on mastery of mechanics, acoustics and the new science of electricity.",
      "His life was one of constant movement and invention. He emigrated first to Cuba, where he worked in a theater in Havana and experimented with using electric currents for medical treatment, and later to New York, settling on Staten Island. Wherever he went he tinkered ceaselessly, devising improvements and new devices in a small home workshop.",
      "In the 1850s, in Havana and then in New York, Meucci developed what he called the telettrofono, a device that could carry the sound of the human voice along an electrical wire from one room to another. According to his accounts, he was partly motivated by personal need: his wife was confined to her bedroom by crippling arthritis, and he rigged a line so they could speak to each other while he worked elsewhere in the house.",
      "But Meucci was perpetually poor, and poverty undid him. He could not afford the substantial fee required to file a full and permanent patent for his invention. Instead, in 1871, he could only manage a caveat, a cheap, temporary notice of an invention in progress that had to be renewed each year, and eventually he could not even afford the small renewal fee, and it lapsed.",
      "A few years later, in 1876, Alexander Graham Bell patented the telephone and went on to fame and immense fortune. Meucci, believing his idea had been taken, spent his final years in bitterness and legal struggle, trying in vain to establish his prior claim, and he died in obscurity in 1889.",
      "History eventually offered him a measure of justice. In 2002, more than a century after his death, the United States House of Representatives passed a resolution formally recognising Antonio Meucci's pioneering work and his contribution to the invention of the telephone. His story endures as a moving reminder that genius and even priority are not always enough, and that some of history's true innovators are recognised only long after they are gone.",
      "On Staten Island his modest home became a refuge for Italian exiles, and for a time he hosted the revolutionary hero Giuseppe Garibaldi, who worked for a while in Meucci's candle factory. Beset by poverty, badly injured in a ferry explosion, and never fully at ease in English, Meucci struggled to defend his work and saw his telephone models lost by a telegraph company. In 2002 the United States House of Representatives, in Resolution 269, formally recognised his contribution to the invention of the telephone, more than a century after his death.",
