      "Giulio Natta was an Italian chemist and chemical engineer who trained at the Politecnico di Milano, where he became a professor and spent his career. He worked at the frontier of one of the most important fields of twentieth century science, the chemistry of polymers, the long chain like molecules from which all plastics are made.",
      "The central challenge in this field was control. A polymer is built by linking thousands of small molecules into a long chain, but the way those links are arranged in space determines everything about the material's properties. Chains that grow in a disorderly tangle tend to make soft, weak, useless substances. The dream was to grow them in a regular, orderly pattern.",
      "Building on a family of catalysts recently discovered by the German chemist Karl Ziegler, Natta achieved exactly this control. In 1954 he produced isotactic polypropylene, a polymer in which every link is arranged in the same regular orientation along the chain. That orderly structure gives the material a remarkable combination of qualities: it is strong, lightweight, heat resistant, chemically stable, easy to mold and very cheap to produce.",
      "Polypropylene went on to become one of the most produced plastics on the entire planet. It is found almost everywhere in daily life, in food packaging and bottle caps, in textiles and carpets, in car bumpers and dashboards, in pipes, containers, furniture and countless pieces of medical equipment such as syringes and sterile packaging.",
      "Natta had, in effect, helped to create the modern plastics industry and the material world of cheap, versatile, mass produced polymers that defines so much of contemporary life. His mastery of stereoregular polymerisation, controlling the three dimensional architecture of giant molecules, was a landmark of materials science.",
      "For this achievement Natta shared the 1963 Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Karl Ziegler. To this day he remains the only Italian ever to have won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry, a distinction that reflects the global importance of the materials he made possible.",
