      "Almost immediately her path was blocked. In 1938 the Fascist regime passed the racial laws, which barred Jews from academic and professional positions and shut her out of her university post. Rather than abandon science, she did something extraordinary: she built a small laboratory in her own bedroom and quietly continued her research, refusing to let persecution end her work.",
      "With astonishing improvisation she carried on, using sewing needles sharpened into surgical instruments and fertilised chicken eggs as her experimental subjects to study how the nervous system develops. As the war intensified and the family was forced into hiding, she repeatedly rebuilt her makeshift laboratory wherever she could, even in the countryside, smuggling out her growing observations on nerve growth.",
      "After the war her brilliance could no longer be hidden, and she was invited to Washington University in St. Louis in the United States, where she carried out the work that would define her career. Through painstaking experiments she discovered nerve growth factor, abbreviated NGF, a protein that signals nerve cells to grow, survive and form the connections that wire the nervous system together.",
      "It was a fundamental and far reaching discovery, the first of a whole family of growth factors that control how the body's cells develop and maintain themselves. It transformed the understanding of how the nervous system is built and opened important avenues of research into cancer, dementia and other diseases. In 1986 she was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for the discovery.",
      "Rita Levi-Montalcini went on to become a revered public figure in Italy, founding research institutes, championing science education and the rights of women, and being appointed a senator for life. Sharp, elegant and active in her laboratory and public life well past the age of one hundred, she became a beloved symbol of resilience, intellectual courage and lifelong curiosity, proof that determination can triumph over even the cruelest obstacles.",
