      "Margherita Hack was born in Florence to free thinking, vegetarian, theosophist parents who raised her to question everything, an upbringing that shaped the fearless and independent character she kept all her life. As a young woman she was also a talented athlete, competing in the long jump and high jump, before she turned decisively to science.",
      "She studied physics at the University of Florence, writing her thesis on a class of stars, and went on to specialise in astrophysics, in particular the study of stars through spectroscopy. This is the art of analysing the light that stars emit, splitting it into its component colors to read off, from a distance of trillions of kilometers, the chemical composition, temperature, motion and physical conditions of a distant sun.",
      "Her talent and energy carried her to the top of Italian science. In 1964 she became the first woman in Italy to be appointed full professor of astronomy, and she took charge of the Trieste Astronomical Observatory, which she rebuilt and modernised into an internationally respected center of research, forging links with the leading observatories and institutions of the world.",
      "But Margherita Hack was far more than a working researcher. She had a rare gift for communication, and she devoted enormous energy to bringing the wonders of the cosmos to ordinary people. Through dozens of popular books, newspaper columns, radio and a constant, lively presence on television, she made astronomy and, just as importantly, rational scientific thinking accessible and exciting to the public.",
      "Outspoken, witty and utterly without pretension, she became a genuine cultural icon in Italy, instantly recognisable for her Florentine accent and her plain spoken honesty. A lifelong atheist, vegetarian and campaigner for civil rights, she never hesitated to speak her mind on science, society and ethics, earning admiration even from those who disagreed with her.",
      "Margherita Hack worked and wrote almost to the end of her long life, dying in 2013 at the age of ninety one. An asteroid, 8558 Hack, is named after her, a small piece of the heavens that now carries the name of the woman who spent her life studying the stars and sharing them, with infectious enthusiasm, with everyone who would listen.",
