      "Carlo Rubbia was born in Gorizia, in northeastern Italy, and grew up fascinated by electrical and mechanical gadgets. He became one of the most influential and forceful experimental physicists of his generation, spending much of his career at CERN, the great European laboratory for particle physics near Geneva, where the deepest questions about the building blocks of matter are explored.",
      "By the late 1970s, physicists had developed a beautiful theory, the electroweak theory, which unified two of nature's four fundamental forces: electromagnetism and the weak nuclear force responsible for certain forms of radioactivity. The theory made a bold prediction: that the weak force must be carried by three very heavy particles, called the W and Z bosons. But no one had ever seen them, and finding them would require energies beyond any existing machine.",
